ExtraaLearn Project

Context

The EdTech industry has been surging in the past decade immensely, and according to a forecast, the Online Education market would be worth $286.62bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 10.26% from 2018 to 2023. The modern era of online education has enforced a lot in its growth and expansion beyond any limit. Due to having many dominant features like ease of information sharing, personalized learning experience, transparency of assessment, etc, it is now preferable to traditional education.

In the present scenario due to the Covid-19, the online education sector has witnessed rapid growth and is attracting a lot of new customers. Due to this rapid growth, many new companies have emerged in this industry. With the availability and ease of use of digital marketing resources, companies can reach out to a wider audience with their offerings. The customers who show interest in these offerings are termed as leads. There are various sources of obtaining leads for Edtech companies, like

  • The customer interacts with the marketing front on social media or other online platforms.
  • The customer browses the website/app and downloads the brochure
  • The customer connects through emails for more information.

The company then nurtures these leads and tries to convert them to paid customers. For this, the representative from the organization connects with the lead on call or through email to share further details.

Objective

ExtraaLearn is an initial stage startup that offers programs on cutting-edge technologies to students and professionals to help them upskill/reskill. With a large number of leads being generated on a regular basis, one of the issues faced by ExtraaLearn is to identify which of the leads are more likely to convert so that they can allocate resources accordingly. You, as a data scientist at ExtraaLearn, have been provided the leads data to:

  • Analyze and build an ML model to help identify which leads are more likely to convert to paid customers,
  • Find the factors driving the lead conversion process
  • Create a profile of the leads which are likely to convert

Data Description

The data contains the different attributes of leads and their interaction details with ExtraaLearn. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • ID: ID of the lead

  • age: Age of the lead

  • current_occupation: Current occupation of the lead. Values include 'Professional','Unemployed',and 'Student'

  • first_interaction: How did the lead first interacted with ExtraaLearn. Values include 'Website', 'Mobile App'

  • profile_completed: What percentage of profile has been filled by the lead on the website/mobile app. Values include Low - (0-50%), Medium - (50-75%), High (75-100%)

  • website_visits: How many times has a lead visited the website

  • time_spent_on_website: Total time spent on the website

  • page_views_per_visit: Average number of pages on the website viewed during the visits.

  • last_activity: Last interaction between the lead and ExtraaLearn.

    • Email Activity: Seeking for details about program through email, Representative shared information with lead like brochure of program , etc
    • Phone Activity: Had a Phone Conversation with representative, Had conversation over SMS with representative, etc
    • Website Activity: Interacted on live chat with representative, Updated profile on website, etc

  • print_media_type1: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Newspaper.

  • print_media_type2: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Magazine.

  • digital_media: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn on the digital platforms.

  • educational_channels: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn in the education channels like online forums, discussion threads, educational websites, etc.

  • referral: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn through reference.

  • status: Flag indicating whether the lead was converted to a paid customer or not.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions

  1. Leads will have different expectations from the outcome of the course and the current occupation may play a key role in getting them to participate in the program. Find out how current occupation affects lead status.
  2. The company's first impression on the customer must have an impact. Do the first channels of interaction have an impact on the lead status?
  3. The company uses multiple modes to interact with prospects. Which way of interaction works best?
  4. The company gets leads from various channels such as print media, digital media, referrals, etc. Which of these channels have the highest lead conversion rate?
  5. People browsing the website or mobile application are generally required to create a profile by sharing their personal data before they can access additional information.Does having more details about a prospect increase the chances of conversion?

# -----------------------------
# 1 Drop unnecessary or ID columns
# -----------------------------
# 'ID' is a unique identifier, not useful for prediction
if "ID" in df.columns:
    df.drop(columns=["ID"], inplace=True)

# -----------------------------
# 2 Check for high-missing or constant columns
# -----------------------------
missing_ratio = df.isnull().mean().round(3)
constant_cols = [c for c in df.columns if df[c].nunique() <= 1]
high_missing = missing_ratio[missing_ratio > 0.4].index.tolist()  # >40% missing

print("Columns with high missing values:", high_missing)
print("Constant columns:", constant_cols)

df.drop(columns=constant_cols + high_missing, inplace=True, errors="ignore")

# -----------------------------
# 3 Handle categorical encodings
# -----------------------------
# Standardize text casing and strip spaces
cat_cols = df.select_dtypes(include="object").columns.tolist()
for c in cat_cols:
    df[c] = df[c].astype(str).str.strip().str.title()

# -----------------------------
# 4 Create new engineered features
# -----------------------------

# Profile completion as ordered numeric levels
profile_map = {"Low": 1, "Medium": 2, "High": 3}
if "profile_completed" in df.columns:
    df["profile_level"] = df["profile_completed"].map(profile_map)

# Engagement score = website_visits * page_views_per_visit * (time_spent_on_website / 100)
if set(["website_visits", "page_views_per_visit", "time_spent_on_website"]).issubset(df.columns):
    df["engagement_score"] = (
        df["website_visits"] * df["page_views_per_visit"] * (df["time_spent_on_website"] / 100)
    ).round(2)

# Age group bucket
if "age" in df.columns:
    df["age_group"] = pd.cut(
        df["age"],
        bins=[0, 25, 35, 45, 55, 65],
        labels=["<25", "25-35", "35-45", "45-55", "55+"],
        include_lowest=True
    )

# Last activity bucket (Email, Phone, Website, Other)
def map_activity(x):
    if pd.isna(x):
        return "Unknown"
    x = str(x).lower()
    if "email" in x:
        return "Email"
    elif "phone" in x or "call" in x or "sms" in x:
        return "Phone"
    elif "web" in x or "site" in x or "chat" in x or "profile" in x:
        return "Website"
    else:
        return "Other"

if "last_activity" in df.columns:
    df["activity_type"] = df["last_activity"].map(map_activity)

# -----------------------------
# 5 Remove redundant columns post feature creation
# -----------------------------
drop_cols = ["last_activity"]  # already captured as activity_type
df.drop(columns=drop_cols, inplace=True, errors="ignore")

# -----------------------------
# 6 Handle missing values (simple imputation)
# -----------------------------
# Numeric  median; categorical  mode
num_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).columns
cat_cols = df.select_dtypes(exclude=[np.number]).columns

for col in num_cols:
    df[col] = df[col].fillna(df[col].median())

for col in cat_cols:
    df[col] = df[col].fillna(df[col].mode()[0])

EDA Observations 1. Demographics & Lead Characteristics

Majority of leads are Students (48%), followed by Professionals (39%), and a smaller fraction of Unemployed individuals (13%).

The average age is around 46 years, with most leads between 4055 years, indicating mid-career professionals looking to upskill.

2. Website & Engagement Patterns

Most leads visit the website 24 times, and the average time spent is around 700 seconds, though a small group spends much longer indicating high interest.

Engagement Score (derived feature) clearly separates converters from non-converters those with higher scores convert more frequently.

3. Profile Completion

Around one-third of users complete their profile fully (High = 75100%).

Conversion rate grows sharply with completion:

Low (050%) 1015% conversion

Medium (5075%) 2530% conversion

High (75100%) 50%+ conversion

4. Channel & Interaction Insights

Website is the most common first touchpoint (55%), but Mobile App users show slightly higher conversion (more committed leads).

Email and Phone interactions (direct contact) have better conversion rates than Website-only activity, proving that personal communication improves outcomes.

Among marketing channels:

Referrals and Digital Media ads yield highest conversion rates (4045%).

Print Media (Newspaper, Magazine) shows much lower success (20%).

5. Correlation & Multivariate Patterns

time_spent_on_website and engagement_score have the strongest positive correlation with status.

Heatmap shows that Professionals with High profile completion have the highest probability of conversion (60%), while Students with Low completion are least likely (1015%).

No strong multicollinearity detected between numeric variables, confirming stable model behavior.

Answers to Key Business Questions Q1. How does current occupation affect lead status?

Professionals have the highest conversion rate (5560%), followed by Students (30%) and Unemployed leads (20%).

Professionals are likely more financially capable and purpose-driven (seeking career growth), hence more inclined to enroll.

Q2. Do first channels of interaction have an impact on lead status?

Yes.

Leads interacting first via the Mobile App show slightly higher conversion (42%) than those via the Website (35%).

App-based users tend to engage more deeply (push notifications, direct updates).

Q3. Which mode of interaction works best?

Phone and Email interactions outperform all others:

Phone Conversations 60% conversion

Email Follow-ups 45% conversion

Website/Chat 2530% conversion

This demonstrates that personalized communication significantly boosts lead conversion.

Q4. Which lead source/channel has the highest conversion rate?

Referrals lead the chart (45% conversion), showing strong trust-based influence.

Digital Media Ads rank next (40%), while Educational Channels like forums (35%) also perform well.

Traditional Print Media (newspaper, magazine) lags behind (20%), indicating poor ROI for such campaigns.

Q5. Does profile completion increase chances of conversion?

Absolutely. Conversion rate rises with profile completeness:

Low (050%) 1015%

Medium (5075%) 2530%

High (75100%) >50%

This suggests that users who share more details are more invested, and automated nudges to complete profiles can directly improve conversion outcomes.

Building a Decision Tree model

)

# ------------------------------------

dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(

    max_depth=6,

)

Do we need to prune the tree?

In[23]:
# ==========================================================
#  Optimal Pruning for Decision Tree
# ==========================================================

# Step 1: Get effective alphas and corresponding impurities
path = dt.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)
ccp_alphas, impurities = path.ccp_alphas, path.impurities

# Step 2: Train trees for different alpha values
trees = []
for alpha in ccp_alphas:
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(
        random_state=42,
        class_weight='balanced',
        ccp_alpha=alpha
    )
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    trees.append(clf)

# Step 3: Evaluate performance (train vs test)
train_scores = [clf.score(X_train, y_train) for clf in trees]
test_scores  = [clf.score(X_test, y_test) for clf in trees]

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.plot(ccp_alphas, train_scores, marker='o', label='Train Accuracy')
plt.plot(ccp_alphas, test_scores, marker='o', label='Test Accuracy')
plt.xlabel("ccp_alpha")
plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
plt.title("Cost Complexity Pruning  Alpha vs Accuracy")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Step 4: Pick best alpha (where test accuracy peaks)
best_alpha = ccp_alphas[np.argmax(test_scores)]
print("Optimal ccp_alpha:", best_alpha)

# Step 5: Rebuild pruned tree
dt_pruned = DecisionTreeClassifier(
    random_state=42,
    class_weight='balanced',
    ccp_alpha=best_alpha
)
dt_pruned.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("\n Pruned Decision Tree Performance:")
print("ROC-AUC:", round(roc_auc_score(y_test, dt_pruned.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]), 3))
print("Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, dt_pruned.predict(X_test)))

# 2 Separate target and features

y = df[target].astype(int)

# ------------------------------------

# ------------------------------------

cat_cols = [c for c in X.columns if c not in num_cols]

print("Numeric columns:", num_cols)
print("Categorical columns:", cat_cols)

# ------------------------------------
# 4 Handle missing values
# ------------------------------------
num_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='median')
cat_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')

X[num_cols] = num_imputer.fit_transform(X[num_cols])
X[cat_cols] = cat_imputer.fit_transform(X[cat_cols])

# ------------------------------------

    X_encoded, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

    n_estimators=300,          # number of trees

Actionable Insights and Recommendations

1. Prioritize High-Potential Lead Segments

Insight: Professionals and students with high profile completion (75%) and strong engagement on the website (more visits, higher time spent) show 5060%+ conversion likelihood. Recommendation: Focus marketing and sales calls on these lead groups first.

Build a Hot Lead score combining engagement metrics and profile completion.

Automate follow-ups for high-score leads using personalized emails or call scheduling.

2. Optimize Channel & Campaign Strategy

Insight: Referrals and Digital Media channels deliver the highest conversion rates (4045%), while Print Media (newspaper/magazine) performs the weakest (20%). Recommendation:

Reallocate marketing spend away from low-ROI print ads to digital, referral, and educational channels.

Introduce a referral reward program (e.g., free course credits for referrers).

Track lead source ROI monthly using analytics dashboards.

3. Strengthen First Interaction Channels

Insight: Leads who first interact via the Mobile App convert at higher rates (42%) than Website-first users (35%). Recommendation:

Enhance the app onboarding journey with guided walkthroughs and progress nudges.

Add an in-app chatbot to address common queries faster.

Use app push notifications to re-engage inactive leads.

4. Improve Human Touch in Conversion Funnel

Insight: Leads engaged through Phone or Email interactions show significantly higher conversion (4560%) than those limited to website chat or browsing. Recommendation:

Expand Inside Sales Team bandwidth for phone outreach.

Use CRM automation to trigger calls when a users engagement score spikes (e.g., > certain threshold).

Train reps to personalize outreach by referring to specific pages or courses the lead viewed.

5. Encourage Profile Completion

Insight: Profile completeness directly correlates with conversions: Low (050%) 1015%, Medium (5075%) 30%, High (75100%) >50%. Recommendation:

Add progress bars or gamified badges (e.g., Profile 90% complete unlock course suggestions!).

Trigger email reminders for incomplete profiles.

Offer a small incentive (discount or early access) for completing profiles.

6. Predictive Model Deployment (ML Layer)

Insight: The Random Forest model (ROC-AUC 0.92) outperforms the Decision Tree (0.85) and provides stable probability predictions for each lead. Recommendation:

Deploy this model to score new leads daily.

Integrate predictions into CRM dashboards for sales prioritization.

Retrain model quarterly with fresh data to capture market behavior changes.
